parameters.name: SC_X
parameters.description:
Spacecraft X position in Heliographic (RTN) coordinates.  
                        The X axis points towards the the first point of Aries 
                        in the solar equatorial plane on the vernal equinox of the        
                        reference epoch 1950 (positive away from the Sun).

parameters.name: SC_Y
parameters.description:
Spacecraft Y position in Heliographic (RTN) coordinates.
                        The Y axis completes the right handed set.

parameters.name: SC_Z
parameters.description:
Spacecraft Z position in Heliographic (RTN) coordinates.
                        The Z axis points along the Sun's spin axis        
                        (positive above the equatorial plane).

parameters.name: VEL_X
parameters.description:
Spacecraft velocity X component in Heliographic (RTN).
                        The X axis points towards the the first point of Aries 
                        in the solar equatorial plane on the vernal equinox of   
                        the reference epoch 1950 (positive away from the Sun).

parameters.name: VEL_Y
parameters.description:
Spacecraft velocity Y component in Heliographic (RTN
                        The Y axis completes the right handed set.

parameters.name: VEL_Z
parameters.description:
Spacecraft velocity Z component in Heliographic (RTN)
                        The Z axis points along the Sun's spin axis 
                        (positive above the equatorial plane).

parameters.name: SC_R
parameters.description:
Heliocentric range from Sun to spacecraft 
                        in units of astronomical units (1 AU = 149674000 km).

parameters.name: SC_LAT
parameters.description:
Spacecraft heliocentric latitude, the angle between the plane           
                        containing the solar spin axis and the solar equatorial plane           
                        (positive above the equatorial plane), in degrees.

parameters.name: SC_LON
parameters.description:
Spacecraft heliocentric longitude (increasing in the direction of       
                        planetary orbital motion) in degrees.
